Pair in a ribbon: MP3 players vs. mobiles.
We help you how to choose
While almost every mobile can play MP3 files, you can’t call with any MP3 player.
This makes it clear that it is better to only buy a phone.
However, there are many reasons to get a separate MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the needs of the future owner.
It’s probably hard to get a high-quality, expensive record player at home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc record.
On the one hand, such music products do not appear on records, but there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
However, if the shelves are full of art rock, jazz or blues bachelor records, then you’re probably dreaming of such a record player.
This is similar to travel, i.e. compressed - simplified with MP3 music.
There are also price and quality categories here.
For some, it may be unacceptable to issue eight thousand crowns for a player, as a Pink Floyd fan probably finds it hard to accept a 20-krone market headphone.
There are two extremes between which everyone has enough space.
The choice is wide.
The lifespan of the elements is also important
Some high-quality music players are capable of much more than simply playing music, but also something that most mobile phones don’t even accidentally do.
None of today’s devices are as versatile as a phone.
In addition to the primary features, phone calls and texting, you can also play music and video, you can record both, you have a better and worse camera, and you can even navigate.
And if we take into account smartphones and communicators, there will also be a small computer in your pocket.
This is a small miracle, as no refrigerator can grill and no TV can photograph.
Multifunctional mobile phones also have disadvantages.
The more features you use on your mobile, the more the display sends to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy regulators.
Few mobile devices are able to play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
With cheap mobiles, therefore, count on the fact that they won’t play for you for a few hours.
In addition, if you’re still on the phone here and there, get even one charger at your workplace for safety reasons – this also applies to more expensive devices.
MP3 players won’t have this problem, even the worst ones can withstand at least 9 hours of continuous operation with a single upload.
The next problem arises when uploading music to your mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices have a universal USB connector and not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without any special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few card readers struggle with the miniature memory cards used in mobile phones without an adapter.
Players with some exceptions (iPods) do not need any special software.
Just charge the device with music from the computer via USB. <0xE2><0x86><0x92>
The majority of mobile phones and players already create their own music library based on the performer's name, the album, the genre, or, for example, the user's assessment.
Some devices only represent a firmware similar to Windows Explorer, and some know both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Players are easier to handle, mobile phones know more
When selecting a specific equipment, first of all, ask about the life of the battery, the capacity of the memory, the quality and type of sound output, and, of course, the convenience of handling.
If your music serves primarily as a background and only listens for a short period of time a day, for example, on the power station, any MP3 player will suit you.
You can actually do this on any mobile phone.
You don’t have to pay special attention to what music formats your mobile or player knows.
Everybody is dealing with MP3, and most of the music that comes to you will be in this format.
MP3 is one of the most popular, and in addition to that, the vast majority of devices also deal with music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and the iPod) is less common.
Better mobiles also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Simply visit the appropriate pages of the provider (or other provider) via the mobile internet and buy the song or album.
This service can in itself be a compelling argument for the purchase of music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of service providers is vague and usually limited to one-year radio stations.
The prices are not the lowest.
In general, however, it is assumed that this kind of selling method of music (whether on GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music market in the future.
Most people keep their mobile phones with them all the time.
Whenever you like to listen to something, your mobile phone rings in your pocket while your forgotten MP3 player is at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry the headphones or at least the speakers.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker, which has almost every mobile, but only a few MP3 players.
For many, the biggest benefit of music mobile phones is likely to be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 crowns.
Between three and four thousand crowns, you can already get a fair walkman.
In most cases, however, you are limited by the lack of output of the traditional headphones.
The best and most technically equipped phones can cost up to fifteen thousand crowns with the traditional 3.5 mm diameter of the headphones.
At the same time, the advantage of the players is, besides the simple handling.
The easiest - not necessarily the most expensive - players (see our selection) are really being handled by everyone.
Minimum function, the previous standard cassette with magnet or gramophone handling is obvious.
There is no threat of collapse in the form of accidentally switched on mobile internet, nor in the case of a huge account for data transfer.
What kind of device to choose
The cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have openings for interchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
You can also purchase the right card for up to two thousand crowns.
But be careful about it.
Basic types only support cards with a maximum capacity of up to 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones can do what with up to 8 GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile and even want to buy cheap MP3 player, choose Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Irivert.
Based on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not need to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you’re among the most demanding students, choose special mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices also have a separate MP3 controller button, the convenience of handling approaches the MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, the most beautiful in the industry, has the same user interface for Walkman series mobiles as the separately sold MP3 players.
MP3 players of the aforementioned brands can provide the same service in the same price category for up to 4,000 crowns, but with greater memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Possibly
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
Nonetheless, there is something missing here - a virtual service provider forcing classical providers to substantially lower prices.
Maybe it won't be that long.
On the Mobil.cz website, we have often written that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in the other EU countries.
After the European Commission’s last move to regulate roaming fees, there may be a conflicting situation – text messages sent from abroad to some of the Czech mobile providers will be cheaper than domestic ones.
How is it possible that the prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacking in the competition that really wants to get into the fight.
This may sound contradictory, because we have three mobile networks and our penetration is high above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile providers would like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, the president of the Czech Telecommunications Office, has often agreed with this, who has previously stated on several occasions that there is no place for a new service provider in the Czech Republic.
Perhaps it’s true that a classic service provider with its own network probably doesn’t have too many chances (although it’s probably already hard to find a frequency).
However, there is another option - the virtual service provider.
The move of virtual service providers to the mobile market brought a significant price drop, after which the classical service providers had to react.
Even before the big fish market, such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, sounds like mine were heard in the UK.
However, it has been proven that such service providers have a place and can really succeed.
However, for example, we do not have to go too far.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
In less than half a year, this service provider has managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider in the country.
Meanwhile, behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among other things.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the ability to focus on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate efficiently, you need far less customers than a traditional service provider.
It does not incur relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers around the world are thus usually presented as low-cost - offering cheap calls and texting, which are often offset by less service.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers at least 50 percent cheaper text messages than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, a good draw can be a good bet on a target group.
This service provider is specially focused on men.
“Real men choose the Mobilking service provider – who they like, who they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company, who operates this virtual service provider.
It’s hard to tell if we have an idea similar to that of Poland.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small in terms of the segmental approach on which the majority of virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory in terms of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, it is unlikely, say mobile providers
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem too hopeful.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for Penta Finance Group, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
In the meantime, he proved that the existing mobile service providers in the Czech Republic were not too familiar with this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything in their power to prevent any potential competition from being created.
For some time now, the GTS Novara Group has not hidden its interest in launching a virtual service provider, which is thus looking to take another step towards making Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in providing our customers not only with wired, but also with mobile telecommunications services.
But the sooner, the better.
We have re-negotiated this option with all Czech mobile providers.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, the group's spokesman.
There may be better times coming.
Unofficial information suggests that the first virtual service provider may be lucky by the end of the year.
His birth, however, is currently surrounded by an impenetrable listening wall.
“At this point, we do not think that a full-fledged virtual service provider would have a place in the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very special.
We have not always been invited by a single entity, offering a complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, the press department of Telefónica 02, told Mobil.cz.
The special situation of the Czech market is also referred to by the other service providers.
Martina Kemrová, spokeswoman for T-Mobile, adds: “We have not recorded a single viable and bilaterally beneficial business project on which we can rely further.”
He added: “In the T-Mobile network, it is unlikely that any virtual service provider will appear before the end of the year.
“At this moment, there should be a concrete agreement on our table so that we can think about it in such a short time.”
Vodafone is focusing on meeting its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are trained to negotiate with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
From the point of view of our customers, we consider this to be the most rewarding.
Vodafone’s main strategy is to partner in this area to build fast mobile networks.”
Responsible offices - a cord with service providers
The procedure of mobile service providers is easy to understand, and the entry of a new service provider would lead to increased competition, lowering prices and thereby reducing their profits.
So why should we facilitate the entry of such a competition?
When service providers are able to cooperate with something important, they also bear witness to the link around the birth of the U:fon.
The biggest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was probably around the birth of T-Mobile’s U:fone.
This is evidenced by the information publicly available on the <0xC4><0x8C>TU website.
But right now U:fon comes as a good reason why we should not allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrová added: "The environment of competition in the mobile market has recently been challenged by the entry of the fourth mobile service provider market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of a new player to the market and its services will support high demands."
However, given the attitude of the mobile service providers, the total lack of interest of the Czech regulatory bodies is quite surprising.
At the same time, it is not just about the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> attitude, which in the Czech Republic unfortunately - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the right to interfere in the economic competition.
Only the Competition Authority has the right to do so.
However, the agency is naturally related to the whole problem.
"The entry of a virtual service provider into the mobile market would only be possible after the contract between a mobile service provider and a virtual service provider is concluded to lease the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties to traditional service providers was probably not sufficiently interesting," said Kristian Chlupua, the Foreign Relations Department of Economic Competition.
A statement thus made by the representatives of the service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from the office, which should represent the interests of consumers and, besides, take care that no one can live back from the market situation, this is more than strange.
As Kristián Chalupa adds, “In the country where virtual service providers usually operate, we can observe that our market entry has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile phone services.”
However, it is likely that the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS do not include the proper functioning of the market environment and the pressure to lower prices.
In this case, a truly shocking consistency resulting from the reaction of the three mobile service providers.
