The Psychology of Overlying: Why We Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
The neuro-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior have been able to be discovered by neuroscientists and economists at the University of New York.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to be in a competition like eBay’s auction, so they’re paying too high a price.
The research attempted to map the nervous system schema of this "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers lottered, the other group participated in the auction of players, while the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method examined the active brain regions of the subjects.
Participants were able to earn money in both games, but during the auction game - in which an essential element is the overindulgence of the other party - the complex called the striatum, under the cervical cortex, went into intensive operation at the time of loss of the game.
This area of the brain plays a role in the "self-supporting" mechanism of the nervous system among several other functions.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the increase in price can be explained by avoiding the heavy reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the members of the research group of economists also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this case, three groups have auctioned against a partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product in question, and they made their bets.
In addition, another group was promised that if they were eliminated from the game, they would receive another <0x24>15 in rewards.
The third group, on the other hand, received <0x24>15 just before the auction, but in the event of a losing auction, the members of the group also lost that money.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, only that one of them emphasized the winning and the other the loss.
Proving the neurologists’ hypothesis, however, members of the team playing against losses were willing to bet higher than the control and the winning group.
“These results cannot be derived from any theory of the economy that existed in the past.
In fact, so far, they have explained only with the joy of winning and the avoidance of risk the phenomena experienced at the auction.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to resolve the contradiction between these two theories by coming to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death.
The number of people with hepatitis at home can be set to one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is the reason: patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the collection name of infectious liver pathways caused by various viruses.
Their lungs have many similarities, characteristic of hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms, depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the feeding channel (for example, with food, water infected), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moisture (poison, vaginal discharge).
Travelers should definitely be protected against A and B viruses, there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, usually accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal complaint, nausea.
After these, yellowing on the skin and white of the eyes develops, the stool becomes clear, the urine becomes dark, and healing can take two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die of the most severe type of the disease, hepatitis B-induced liver cancer and liver fat.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten people who are infected will receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver constriction and liver cancers.
Most infected people don’t even know about their disease, because the pathogen subcutaneously destroys the cells of the liver, in many cases the first symptoms appear only after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prematurely prevent and to carry out regular screening tests.
In three groups, such diseases are far more than the average: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users, and tattooists.
The number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is currently 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is worth consulting a pharmacist if any symptoms of unknown origin are detected.
With the recognition of time, the disease can be cured, the virus can be removed from the body, thus eliminating the infectious ability and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients around the world.
It aims to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
