The flight of the dong is imitated by the smart car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to avoid collisions if it weren’t for imitation of obstacle sensors in the natural world?
Bees, for example.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the dong bees gave Nissan engineers a strategic starting point in how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C, a two-wheeled car robotic control system, a robotic mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate purpose of designing a system that will help to prevent it from developing.
During flight, each bee forms its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective bucket - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, Technology PR and R&D Brand Director at the exhibition.
The role of the complex eye of the uterus is important, which can be seen at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions.
To copy the complex function of the eye, the engineers came up with the idea of laser telemetry.
This detects obstacles within a distance of 2 meters before 180 degrees before the BR23C, calculates their distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into a collision avoidance operation.
During the fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected, and then the car robot, following the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid collision.
In any way that is different from the current system, this avoidance maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If it weren’t, the car robot wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, the head of the car robot project at the Mobility Laboratory.
It must react in a stimulating manner and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the safety shields, a layer within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does in order to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in a single click of an eye.
But, unlike bees, the deviation cannot be directed upwards, downwards, or transversely, it can be only two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the wheels’ reversibility.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibility available to bees to escape other bees, only rotary motion and acceleration, as well as the slowdown, were applied as an option available to the car robot.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variables.
According to Andoh, an instinctive intelligent response is an important, not the ability to process data, even less the ability to store it.
This structure needs to process only a few incoming signals every second and respond to them.
There’s no need to preserve them and respond with intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres, so you’re constantly using only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of a technology for immediate avoidance, which Nissan estimates could be involved in series-produced cars within ten years.
It may be possible to integrate the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to drive the car to the specified destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
